      "writtenOn": "2020-07-30T09:18:52Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Thanks for your honesty (though I rarely expect less from you 😄).\nI didn\u0027t mean to insist and I don\u0027t. I actually like careful tagging you are doing here. What I meant above was that L376...L377 comment !\u003d code and I was expecting you to update the comment.\n\n**Personally** and this should not affect this CL:\nI don\u0027t hate multierrors, I consider them for the most part essential complexity, which however can be hidden behind Error interface for code chunks, which don\u0027t need to care about nature of the error. And, when debugging, I find full error graph very useful together stack for each of the error origin (a bit like what uncaught panic() prints on stderr). I do agree that in Go this is super duper annoying to do. I still can\u0027t help but curse every time I have to type error.Annotate 😞\n\n\u003e I just remove the outer wrapping of errors.MultiError and let callers shoot their own feet on their own accord.\n\nI definitely don\u0027t like this. Do you have any reason for doing it other than satisfying my presumed insistence in original review? If not, please undo.",
